01:19:44.720 --> 01:19:49.880
But the answer is that, once
we decouple those high energy

01:19:49.880 --> 01:19:54.230
modes, then you can just
extend to whatever energy range

01:19:54.230 --> 01:19:55.300
you want.

01:19:55.300 --> 01:19:57.690
Because you have served
the purpose of discover--

01:19:57.690 --> 01:20:00.730
decouple those-- yeah,
because those things already

01:20:00.730 --> 01:20:02.060
went to infinity.

01:20:02.060 --> 01:20:05.360
You don't have to
worry about them.

01:20:05.360 --> 01:20:05.860
Is it clear?

01:20:08.440 --> 01:20:10.409
Just like in the
Yang-Mills theory,

01:20:10.409 --> 01:20:11.950
we said we take the
low energy limit.

01:20:11.950 --> 01:20:14.092
We decouple those massive modes.

01:20:14.092 --> 01:20:15.800
But eventually, in
the Yang-Mills theory,

01:20:15.800 --> 01:20:17.820
we would consider very
high energy processing

01:20:17.820 --> 01:20:20.990
in the Yang-Mills theory.

01:20:20.990 --> 01:20:21.900
OK?

01:20:21.900 --> 01:20:26.386
But those things we decouple
have even higher energy scale.

01:20:26.386 --> 01:20:26.886
OK?

01:20:30.310 --> 01:20:33.010
Good, good, good.

01:20:33.010 --> 01:20:38.770
So we call this-- so
this is 1 and this is 2.

01:20:38.770 --> 01:20:41.970
So in fact, actually
1 and 2, they're

01:20:41.970 --> 01:20:47.300
not covering the full
anti-de Sitter spacetime.

01:20:47.300 --> 01:20:48.855
So actually, they
only cover a part

01:20:48.855 --> 01:20:51.090
of anti-de Sitter spacetime.

01:20:51.090 --> 01:20:55.530
So they only cover, say, what
is so-called Poincare patch,

01:20:55.530 --> 01:20:59.200
a patch of de-Sitter spacetime,
anti-de Sitter spacetime.

01:20:59.200 --> 01:21:02.470
So now let me just mention a
little bit what is normally

01:21:02.470 --> 01:21:03.900
called a global AdS.

01:21:03.900 --> 01:21:04.950
OK?

01:21:04.950 --> 01:21:13.120
So the AdS, or global
AdS-- so let me first

01:21:13.120 --> 01:21:14.310
write down this sentence.

01:21:14.310 --> 01:21:32.660
So 1, 2-- 1 over 2 only
covers a part of full AdS.

01:21:37.520 --> 01:21:40.220
OK?

01:21:40.220 --> 01:21:48.380
So the global AdS, the
so-called global AdS,

01:21:48.380 --> 01:21:57.380
can be defined--
can be described

01:21:57.380 --> 01:22:00.411
as a hyperboloid in
the Lorentz spacetime.

01:22:00.411 --> 01:22:00.910
OK?

01:22:03.420 --> 01:22:15.615
Hyperboloid in Minkowski--
d plus 2 Minkowski

01:22:15.615 --> 01:22:22.730
spacetime of signature 2, d.

01:22:22.730 --> 01:22:24.080
OK?

01:22:24.080 --> 01:22:30.880
So to make this precise,
say, for example,

01:22:30.880 --> 01:22:33.380
if you go to the
[INAUDIBLE]-- for example,

01:22:33.380 --> 01:22:39.120
the book by Hawking and
Ellis called The Large Scale

01:22:39.120 --> 01:22:44.990
Structure of Spacetime, the way
they define the anti-de Sitter

01:22:44.990 --> 01:22:47.220
as follows.

01:22:47.220 --> 01:22:52.730
So you consider d + 2 dimension
of Minkowski spacetime

01:22:52.730 --> 01:22:55.340
with signature 2, d.

01:22:55.340 --> 01:22:59.850
So you consider a Minkowski
spacetime like this.

01:23:12.999 --> 01:23:14.460
OK?

01:23:14.460 --> 01:23:18.850
So now you have d,
positive signature,

01:23:18.850 --> 01:23:20.960
and the two negative signature.

01:23:20.960 --> 01:23:26.050
So x starts from minus 1
index to 0, which gives you

01:23:26.050 --> 01:23:27.770
the negative signature.

01:23:27.770 --> 01:23:31.170
And then you have-- so this is
Minkowski spacetime of the 2,

01:23:31.170 --> 01:23:33.930
d signature.

01:23:33.930 --> 01:23:36.650
So now you can see that
the following hyper surface

01:23:36.650 --> 01:23:37.400
in that spacetime.

01:23:50.470 --> 01:23:52.460
OK?

01:23:52.460 --> 01:23:56.410
So this is a hyperboloid
in that spacetime.

01:23:56.410 --> 01:23:58.760
And this defines your AdS.

01:23:58.760 --> 01:23:59.260
OK?

01:23:59.260 --> 01:24:01.090
So this surface defines AdS.

01:24:06.000 --> 01:24:08.330
This surface defines AdS.

01:24:12.430 --> 01:24:14.280
So, of course, this is
a very different way

01:24:14.280 --> 01:24:18.850
to parametrize AdS.

01:24:18.850 --> 01:24:20.920
Then either this
metric or that metric.

01:24:23.610 --> 01:24:25.350
And you can actually
parametrize AdS

01:24:25.350 --> 01:24:27.150
in many, many different ways.

01:24:27.150 --> 01:24:29.550
So now let me just
mention a few ways

01:24:29.550 --> 01:24:33.420
to-- a few choices of different
coordinates to parametrize

01:24:33.420 --> 01:24:34.251
this hyperboloid.

01:24:34.251 --> 01:24:34.750
OK?

01:24:37.780 --> 01:24:40.650
So the first is-- one is called
the Poincare coordinates.

01:24:40.650 --> 01:24:41.470
It's this one.

01:24:53.800 --> 01:24:57.490
So first is what we call
the Poincare coordinates.

01:24:57.490 --> 01:25:00.600
So in this Poincare
coordinates, you introduce r.

01:25:00.600 --> 01:25:07.410
So r there is given
by x minus 1 plus xd.

01:25:07.410 --> 01:25:10.980
So you take the 1 over
the negative signature

01:25:10.980 --> 01:25:13.352
and the 1 over the
positive signature.

01:25:13.352 --> 01:25:16.150
You take x minus 1xd,
add them together.

01:25:16.150 --> 01:25:19.270
So this is like some
kind of [INAUDIBLE].

01:25:19.270 --> 01:25:23.600
And then you write x mu.

01:25:23.600 --> 01:25:30.366
So there, we always
write x mu equal to tx.

01:25:30.366 --> 01:25:31.220
OK?

01:25:31.220 --> 01:25:33.935
So this is a three-dimensional
Minkowski coordinate.

01:25:33.935 --> 01:25:44.510
You add x mu equal to r times
capital mu divided by r.

01:25:44.510 --> 01:25:46.630
OK?

01:25:46.630 --> 01:25:56.370
So in this hyperboloid,
you make this definition.

01:25:56.370 --> 01:25:59.270
And then you restrict to the
region of r greater than 0.

01:26:02.450 --> 01:26:04.340
Then you recover.

01:26:04.340 --> 01:26:16.700
So 1 corresponds to r greater
than 0 part of this metric,

01:26:16.700 --> 01:26:18.154
of this spacetime.

01:26:18.154 --> 01:26:19.570
And you can easily
check yourself.

01:26:19.570 --> 01:26:23.310
Just make this definition-- this
is the exercise you should do,

01:26:23.310 --> 01:26:25.080
which I don't have
time to do here.

01:26:25.080 --> 01:26:26.710
Just plug this in.

01:26:26.710 --> 01:26:29.680
Plug this into that metric.

01:26:29.680 --> 01:26:32.350
Plug this parametrization
into that metric,

01:26:32.350 --> 01:26:36.050
and then you find
you will recover 1.

01:26:36.050 --> 01:26:40.260
Of course, 1 is only restricted
to r equal to 0 to infinity.

01:26:40.260 --> 01:26:44.357
So you only restrict to r
greater than 0 part of this.

01:26:44.357 --> 01:26:46.690
And if you just introduce
this in [INAUDIBLE], of course

01:26:46.690 --> 01:26:48.471
r can be smaller than 0.

01:26:48.471 --> 01:26:48.970
OK?

01:26:51.520 --> 01:26:53.680
So these are
Poincare coordinates.

01:26:53.680 --> 01:26:56.620
So once you go to that metric,
you then go to this metric.

01:26:56.620 --> 01:26:58.974
It's the same.

01:26:58.974 --> 01:27:00.390
Now also let me
describe something

01:27:00.390 --> 01:27:01.640
called the global coordinates.

01:27:12.810 --> 01:27:16.810
So this is-- if I notice
the following structure.

01:27:16.810 --> 01:27:23.240
So this has the form of the
difference of two squares.

01:27:23.240 --> 01:27:32.670
So I can write-- so
let's write xi to 1

01:27:32.670 --> 01:27:38.120
to d xi squared to
be some function,

01:27:38.120 --> 01:27:40.920
r squared and r squared--
times r squared.

01:27:40.920 --> 01:27:43.490
So this r have nothing
to do with that r now.

01:27:43.490 --> 01:27:45.770
We are doing a different
set of coordinates.

01:27:45.770 --> 01:27:48.975
I'm just using the same
notation for convenience.

01:27:51.540 --> 01:27:54.890
So let's introduce a new
coordinate, r, which is just

01:27:54.890 --> 01:27:58.070
the sum of all these squared.

01:27:58.070 --> 01:28:02.335
And then I introduce--
then from this equation,

01:28:02.335 --> 01:28:07.460
the x1 minus x0 squared
should be equal to r

01:28:07.460 --> 01:28:11.650
squared plus 1 times r squared.

01:28:11.650 --> 01:28:12.150
OK?

01:28:15.570 --> 01:28:20.070
So now I can-- so
this is a circle.

01:28:20.070 --> 01:28:21.850
So for fixed r,
this is a circle.

01:28:24.420 --> 01:28:29.400
For fixed r, this is a d
minus 1 dimensional sphere.

01:28:29.400 --> 01:28:31.160
OK?

01:28:31.160 --> 01:28:35.560
So I can introduce the d minus
1 spherical coordinates on this

01:28:35.560 --> 01:28:38.880
and then introduce a
circular coordinate on this.

01:28:38.880 --> 01:28:42.080
So if I do that--
so let me just call

01:28:42.080 --> 01:28:46.890
the circular coordinate on
here tau, the polar coordinate

01:28:46.890 --> 01:28:49.000
in the x minus y.

01:28:51.520 --> 01:29:03.380
Polar coordinate in the x
minus 1 and the x0 plane.

01:29:03.380 --> 01:29:04.730
So let me call this tau.

01:29:04.730 --> 01:29:06.880
And let me call
[INAUDIBLE] coordinate

01:29:06.880 --> 01:29:11.020
here omega d minus 1.

01:29:11.020 --> 01:29:12.960
OK?

01:29:12.960 --> 01:29:16.270
Then you plug this into here.

01:29:16.270 --> 01:29:18.316
Then you find the
following metric.

01:29:30.640 --> 01:29:33.310
So you find the
following metric.

01:29:33.310 --> 01:29:44.005
You find ds squared equal to r
squared minus 1 plus r squared

01:29:44.005 --> 01:29:53.790
d tau squared plus the r
squared plus 1 plus r squared

01:29:53.790 --> 01:29:59.080
plus r squared d omega
d minus 1 squared.

01:29:59.080 --> 01:29:59.580
OK?

01:30:10.910 --> 01:30:13.310
So remember, tau is
the polar coordinate

01:30:13.310 --> 01:30:15.910
in this x minus 1 and x0 plane.

01:30:15.910 --> 01:30:19.420
And the omega d minus 1 is
the polar coordinate in the x1

01:30:19.420 --> 01:30:23.560
to xd OK?

01:30:23.560 --> 01:30:26.019
And then you get this.

01:30:26.019 --> 01:30:28.310
Again, it's an exercise you
should go through yourself.

01:30:28.310 --> 01:30:28.760
Yes?

01:30:28.760 --> 01:30:29.110
AUDIENCE: So I have a question.

01:30:29.110 --> 01:30:30.568
So I'm just trying
